By the good idea from Tyma Gaidash, using the Faa di Bruno formula and the formulas in the question, we can give a satisfactory answer as follows:

Becase
$$x^{\lambda/x}=\biggl(\frac1x\biggr)^{-\lambda/x}=u\biggl(\frac1x\biggr),$$
where
$u(t)=t^{-\lambda t}$
, we arrive at
\begin{multline}
\bigl[(1+x)^{\lambda/(1+x)}\bigr]^{(n)}=\biggl[\biggl(\frac1{1+x}\biggr)^{-\lambda/(1+x)}\biggr]^{(n)}\\
\begin{aligned}
&=\sum_{k=0}^n [u(t)]^{(k)} B_{n,k}\biggl(\biggl(\frac1{1+x}\biggr)',\biggl(\frac1{1+x}\biggr)'',\dotsc,\biggl(\frac1{1+x}\biggr)^{(n-k+1)}\biggr)\\
&=\sum_{k=0}^n\Biggl[k!x^{-\lambda x-k}\sum_{i=0}^{k}(-\lambda)^i x^{i} \sum_{j=0}^{i} \Biggl[\sum_{q=0}^{k-i} \frac{s(q+j,j)}{(q+j)!} \binom{j}{k-i-q}\Biggr] \frac{(\ln x)^{i-j}}{(i-j)!}\Biggr]B_{n,k}\dotsm\\
&=\dotsm
\end{aligned}
\end{multline}
Done! Thank Tyma Gaidash for the good idea!

Finally, we acquire
\begin{multline}
\bigl[(1+x)^{\lambda/(1+x)}\bigr]^{(k)}
=(-1)^kk!\biggl(\frac{1}{1+x}\biggr)^{k-\lambda/(1+x)} \sum_{j=0}^{k}\binom{k-1}{j-1} \sum_{i=0}^{j}\lambda^i \biggl[\frac{\ln(1+x)}{1+x}\biggr]^{i}\\
\times\sum_{\ell=0}^{i} \Biggl[\sum_{q=0}^{j-i} \frac{s(q+\ell,\ell)}{(q+\ell)!} \binom{\ell}{j-i-q}\Biggr] \frac{(-1)^{\ell}}{(i-\ell)![\ln(1+x)]^{\ell}}
\end{multline}
and, equivalently,
\begin{multline}
\bigl(x^{\lambda/x}\bigr)^{(k)}
=(-1)^kk!\biggl(\frac{1}{x}\biggr)^{k-\lambda/x} \sum_{j=0}^{k}\binom{k-1}{j-1} \sum_{i=0}^{j}\lambda^i \biggl(\frac{\ln x}{x}\biggr)^{i}\\
\times\sum_{\ell=0}^{i} \Biggl[\sum_{q=0}^{j-i} \frac{s(q+\ell,\ell)}{(q+\ell)!} \binom{\ell}{j-i-q}\Biggr] \frac{(-1)^{\ell}}{(i-\ell)!(\ln x)^{\ell}}.
\end{multline}

