Natanson is referring to midpoint (Jensen) convexity, where the "everywhere discontinuous" examples are actually non-measurable solutions to Cauchy’s Functional Equation (
$f(x+y) = f(x) + f(y)$
) constructed via a Hamel basis, which lack the local boundedness required to bridge the gap to standard continuity. There are no simple counterexamples to this problem, as local boundedness above is sufficient to imply continuity; consequently, any valid counterexample must be everywhere discontinuous.
